Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline they lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is as fresh  as the need to sail the Pacific again.
That hope is probably the highest it has been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the international court of justice on October 1, after 5 years of negotiations.
"Bolivia has the momentum, the spirit of unity and peace, and naturally expects the outcome with a positive attitude", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the IGH ruling on big screens across the country, hoping that the tribunal in The Hague will find in favor of Bolivia's claim that  after decades of sporadic negotiations  Chile is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia a sovereign passage to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president  who faces a controversial re-election battle next year  also has a lot to decide on Monday's ruling.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific", he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court's decision in Bolivia's favor is unlikely  and that little will change if it does.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to award Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
