Morales' aggressive rhetoric tapped into any remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold such talks.
The last time the two countries exchanged ambassadors was in 1962.
Former president Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision was extremely swift.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of differences for mutual benefit", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales  still one of Latin America's most popular presidents  uses the maritime issue as a political crutch.
