John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a string of achievements of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, only reinforced by individual and collective successes in sport, the arts, music and other community enterprises.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and their position as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see world languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart".
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of scholars who studied foreign languages received an A above grade.
The data, collected from SCIS' 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students scored an upper A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 of those studying French, and 63 of those studying Spanish also scored an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages now have the same status as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and math) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Occupations and Skills found that 17 percent of the reasons given by employees for their difficulty filling jobs were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, learning a second language will give them a real advantage in the future with such a life-long skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically put a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to engage in conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why it is now so important to invest in language education for today's children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered essential for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interests, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still hugely important for the future of the country, and therefore should be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
We must do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
