North Korea says it will 'definitely not' unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions are deepening their distrust of the United States and that the country will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such characteristics.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken "meaningful goodwill measures" in the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the United States", he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances we will certainly not unilaterally disarm first".
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea if it took gradual steps, his words seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament unconditionally as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri was referring to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim pledged to work for the "destruction of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula" while Trump pledged guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The US insists on 'destruction of nuclear weapons first' and is putting more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve its goal in a compelling way, even objecting to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can force us to our knees is a dream of people who are ignorant about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our distrust".
Ri did not say anything about plans for a second Kim-Trump summit that the US leader drew attention to earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings over the past five months between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in, adding: "If the party in this nuclear destruction issue were South Korea and not the United States, the destruction of nuclear weapons on the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a dead end".
Ri's tone of speech was dramatically different from last year, however, when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea's missiles would inevitably be aimed at the US mainland after "Mr. Bad President" Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, lavished praise on Kim for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but said much work still needed to be done and that sanctions would remain in place until North Korea destroyed its nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this, saying, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years, or five months".
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that: "The implementation of sanctions by the Security Council must continue diligently and without interruption until we achieve the complete, final, verified destruction of nuclear weapons".
The Security Council has been unanimously tightening sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an attempt to dry up funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and said afterwards that he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying progress had been made, but just hours later North Korea accused him of making "gang demands".
North Korea promised in a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "corresponding measures".
He said Kim told him that the "compliant measures" he wants to see are security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore as well as steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is getting all its undergraduate students to get more sleep in an effort to counter the growing macho culture of studying through caffeinated "all-nights sessions".
One academic found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant of the basics of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of it, one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was - which surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, offered for the first time that year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how they improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were severely sleep deprived during the week.
The one-hour course involves some interactive tasks.
In one section there is a picture of a dormitory where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes, and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are told how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know that this will not change student behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in 'studying all night' still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students have meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Making sure you get enough good-quality sleep should be a student's "secret weapon" to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even weight gain, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in starvation mode, leaving you feeling hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to pursue a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
