Speaking on the first Radio 4 Desert Island Discs hosted by Lauren Laverne, he said he was venting his feelings about gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that becoming a parent made him less concerned about winning at the Olympics.
The longtime regular host of the program, Kirsty Young, took a few months off because of illness.
When he appeared as a rejectionist on Laverne's first show, Daley said he felt "less" than everyone else growing up because "it was not socially acceptable to like boys and girls".
He said: "To this day, those feelings of inferiority and different feeling are the real things that gave me the strength and energy to succeed".
He wanted to prove he was "something", he said, so that he would not disappoint anyone when they finally found out about his sexuality.
The double Olympic bronze medalist has become a high-profile LGBT activist and used his appearance at this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He says that he has vented his feelings because he is so happy to live openly without consequences and wants to give others "hope".
The three-time world champion said falling in love with US filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, "took him by surprise".
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, who is 20 years older than him, but says the age difference has never been an issue.
