Germany's new warship postponed again
The German army's newest frigate was due to enter service in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but it won't be there until at least next year, due to faulty systems and rising costs, local media reports.
The commissioning of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the lead ship of the brand new Baden-Wuerttemberg-class frigates has now been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper quoting a military spokesman.
This vessel was due to join the Navy in 2014, but the troubling post-delivery issues plagued the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is understood that they will have a powerful cannon, a battle array of air defense and anti-ship missiles as well as several secret technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods  it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years away from home.
But continuing delays mean that the advanced warships  that will apparently enable Germany to project power overseas  will already be obsolete by the time they enter service, notes Die Zeit.
The disastrous F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media have mentioned that a number of essential "software and hardware defects" render the ship useless if deployed in a campaign.
Software flaws are particularly important as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be handled by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half the manpower on older Bremen-class frigates.
