The National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research is being conducted on an estate in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common and super-midget bats as well as the brown langur and Daubenton bats at Invereve Gardens in West Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations on the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld indicators.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will check the frequency of the bat calls and determine which species are doing so.
A habitat map and report will then be compiled to create a detailed landscape scale picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management such as grazing and how to best manage forest land for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined dramatically over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects their sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can flypaper and some chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting activities, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo-orientation technique to point out bugs and obstacles on their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens, and 76,000 acres of land across the country, is very serious about bats.
It has ten trained specialists who regularly conduct surveys and sleeping inspections and sometimes perform rescues.
The organisation has even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal site for them.
"Here at Threave we have a wonderful area for bats", he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still so much about bats that is unknown, so the work we do here and on other properties helps us to better understand what they need to thrive".
He stresses the need to search for bats before doing maintenance on properties because it is possible that unintentional destruction of a single nursery could result in the deaths of up to 400 females and young and wipe out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or interfere with them or destroy their habitat.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to jump in to help.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations fare.
