In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster struck.
Here are some key facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, located at the tip of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami struck.
Donggala is a regency that stretches along more than 300 km (180 mi) of coastline in the northwest of Sulawesi island.
The county, an administrative region under a province, had an estimated population of 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the mainstays of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, especially the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mostly concentrated in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times during the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938 a tsunami killed over 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also struck western Donggala in 1996, killing nine.
Indonesia sits on the seismic Pacific Ring of Fire and is frequently struck by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: A major earthquake along the western coast of Indonesia's Aceh province in northern Sumatra on December 26 that led to a tsunami that hit 14 countries, resulting in 226,000 deaths along the Indian Ocean coast, with more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8 magnitude quake hit southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, leading to a tsunami that hit the southern coast and caused nearly 700 deaths.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near the city of Padang, capital of West Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake hits one of the Mentawai Islands, near Sumatra, causing a 10-meter-high tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A massive earthquake hit the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh and led to destruction and panic as people were reminded of the devastation of the deadly 2004 quake and tsunami.
It didn't lead to a tsunami this time, but more than 100 people died from collapsed buildings,
2018: Major earthquakes hit Indonesia's tourist island of Lombok, with more than 500 deaths, mostly on the northern side of the island.
The quake destroyed thousands of buildings and temporarily stranded thousands of tourists.
